<DOC><DOCNO> AP890722-0152 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0103EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-KFCPresident     07-22 0278</FIRST><SECOND>AM-KFC President,0288</SECOND><HEAD>John M. Cranor III Appointed President, CEO of Kentucky Fried Chicken</HEAD><DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   John M. Cranor III, a top executive atPepsico Inc., was appointed Friday as president and chief executiveof the food and soft drink maker's Kentucky Fried Chicken Corp.subsidiary.   Cranor, 42, formerly president of Pepsi-Cola East, will succeedRichard P. Mayer, who resigned to become president of General FoodsU.S.A., said D. Wayne Calloway, chairman of the board and chiefexecutive of Pepsico, based in Purchase, N.Y.   ``We're very fortunate to have a leader of John Cranor's caliberto succeed Dick,'' Calloway said in a news release. ``We have greatconfidence in the entire KFC organization, and look forward to evengreater success in the years ahead under John's leadership.''   KFC is the world's second-largest quick service restaurantsystem with about 8,000 restaurants generating sales of nearly $6billion. It was acquired by PepsiCo in October 1986.   Cranor has held a series of marketing, operations and generalmanagement positions in the restaurant, soft drinks and snack foodbusinesses.   He began his PepsiCo career in 1977 as marketing group managerat Frito-Lay, where he eventually served as vice president of newbusiness development and vice president of marketing.   Cranor then was a senior vice president and later president ofWilson Sporting Goods, then a Pepsico subsidiary.   In 1985, he joined Taco Bell and became division vice president,making him responsible for 1,300 restaurants in the United States.He then became president of PepsiCo's Fountain Beverage operationsin 1986.   Cranor was promoted to president of Pepsi-Cola East in February1988, making him responsible for all Pepsi operations in theNortheast.</TEXT></DOC>